1. Setting Up Your Environment
Before importing, ensure your data file is in your Working Directory.

# Check where R is looking for files
getwd() 

# Pro-Tip: Use RStudio Projects (.Rproj) to handle directories automatically!
2. Importing Data
Find your Excel file in the Files pane in RStudio.

Click the file and select Import Dataset...

Important: If your Excel sheet doesn't have headers, uncheck "First Row as Names" in the import window.

3. Formatting Column & Row Names
Once your data (let's call it Data) is in the Environment, we need to label the columns.

Critical: Avoid using "k" or symbols in column names if you plan to convert them to numbers later. Use plain numbers for concentrations.

R

# Assigning clear, numeric column names
colnames(Data) <- c("0", "10", "15", "5") 
rownames(Data) <- c("rep1", "rep2", "rep3")

# Add metadata columns to track different plates or timepoints
Data$Plate <- 1
Data$Hour  <- 1
4. Converting to Long Format
R graphs work best with "Long" data. We use tidyr::pivot_longer() to stack our concentrations into a single column.

library(tidyr)

long_data <- pivot_longer(
  Data,
  cols = c("0", "5", "10", "15"), # These match your colnames above
  names_to = "Cells",
  values_to = "Absorbance"
)
5. Combining Multiple Plates
If you have multiple plates (e.g., long_data2, long_data3), combine them into one master dataset for easier graphing.


library(dplyr)

# Stack all datasets vertically
Combined_data <- bind_rows(long_data, long_data2, long_data3)

# Verify the result
head(Combined_data)



